<br>
&quot;Bravo! Bravo!&quot; he laughed and clapped as he glided his way to Aphrodite.<br>
<br>
He perked his brow to her, his ever present smirk trickling onto his face. His eyes wandered to Paris, that poor dim-witted boy. Apollo walked to him and offered his hand. The young Paris looked up at Apollo, the god he had prayed to on all those sundays, the day most sacred to Phoebus Apollo. And on the seventh day of each month, where he would cease working to gather hetacombs and sacrafice them in the name of King Apollo.<br>
<br>
His trembling hand reached up and made contact with the silky smooth skin of Apollo. He stood, and found Apollo's arm wrapped around his neck, as if they were old friends. A smile arose to his face, he felt important now. Not just such of a shepherd. He was someone, he was going to live it up with Phoebus Apollo himself.<br>
<br>
&quot;Quite a day you've had eh?&quot; Apollo whispered to Paris, as they walked from the halls of the great temple upon the magnificent cliff in which the wedding took place. The two walked far from the temple to a valley about half a mile from the temple itself.<br>
<br>
It was only then that Paris had responded a simple &quot;Yes.&quot; to Apollo's question. He took the whole moment to drink up all that had just happened to him. It was to say the least world toppling to think that he would be chosen to judge the contest. And be bribed along with it. He considered himself a blessed man. He shook the chestnut brown hair from his blue eyes and smiled to Apollo.<br>
<br>
&quot;The made me bribes, Far-shooting Apollo. By some awkward will of Aegis-bearing Zeus, they had chosen me, a mere shepherd boy, to be judge. And it is for you, King Apollo, that I owe this fortune to. If not for you, I would have just been a spectator to this magnificent historical event. All you have done for me is countless Apollo. You have protected my herds, you have guided my from boyhood to manhood. It is by your sweet gestures that my fields grow. By your protection my herds stay safe from the wolves at night. Your wonders never cease. For this I owe to you my mortal soul, Apollo, son of Aegis-bearing Zeus, and the benevolent Titaness.&quot; he bowed his head, duely to Apollo.<br>
<br>
Apollo outstretched his hand and raised the head of Paris, a warm smile on his face. The sunlight glowed behind him. As Paris's eyes met those of Apollo it was as if the god was a painting, like this was all a weird dream. Apollo shook the hair from his eyes and spoke, taking his eyes off of Paris and staring out into nothing.<br>
<br>
&quot;It is by labor by myself that your crops grow plentiful, your herds protected, and you yourself become a man. These are things that without my help, would undoubtedly happen, but it is by my will that I encourage them. It is I who oversees these miracles, and ensures their happenings. Paris, fair, handsome Paris, it is by will of the Fates themselves that you were chosen on this day. Not even Father Zeus could alter the happenings and orders of the Fates, their word is the last. Your actions today will have repercussions. Indeed they will have repercussions.&quot; Apollo shook his head a bit.<br>
<br>
&quot;But some things have got to happen. Change is apart of the natural cycle of things. Keep that in mind young Paris. For when you are ripened old man, you will need my words. Change is a part of the cycle. Take each lose, and each win in stride. Do not grow arrogance in your advancements, or they will be your undoing. Whomever you chose, I want you to promise me you will chose from your heart.&quot; Apollo poked Paris's chest.<br>
<br>
&quot;For it is from here where Aegis-bearing Father Zeus, and I, Phoebus Apollo, talk to you. It is from you heart all your hopes and dreams come from. But this is not what I brought you out here to tell. I have already gone over that. Paris, whomever you choose today...well...things will happen. Just take them in stride. Now let us go back to the party.&quot; Apollo stood, and again offered Paris his hand. And together they strode back to the temple.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#6A74B4><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub11.ezboard.com/uposeidonkofc.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Poseidonkofc</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Silver Warrior</span><br>  Posts: 224<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(11/24/01 12:32:09 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub11.ezboard.com/famazonsunitefrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2.topic&index=160>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Old Slouch</span><hr size=1> ::Poseidon leans back in the chair and folds his arms across his chest while the beauty, how should he say it, pageant continues. He shakes his head looking at Apollo getting into everyone's business and sucks his teeth at him. He then talks to himself grumpily about Apollo.::<br>
